on in our lives. Forgetting and memory, far from being autonomous and mutually exclusive spheres, should be seen as interdependent phenomena. Drawing on perspectives from history, philosophy, literature, and religion, and examining both transmitted texts and excavated materials, the contributors to this volume analyze various ways of understanding oblivion and its complex and fertile relations with memory in ancient China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aChinese literaturey221 B.C.-960 A.D.xHistory and criticism. 0aChinese literatureyTo 221 B.C.xHistory and criticism. 0aMemory. 0aPhilosophy, Chinesey221 B.C.-960 A.D. 0aPhilosophy, ChineseyTo 221 B.C. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Confucianism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Taoism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aBrashier, K. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalvany, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIng, Michael D. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Esther Sunkyung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrijgsman, Rens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Xiang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilburn, Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerkins, Franklin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValmisa, Mercedes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVan Auken, Newell Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVogt, Paul Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZürn, Tobias Benedikt,